    "original_title": "IOM Flies 56 Migrants Back to Ethiopia",
    "slug": "iom-returns-56-ethiopian-migrants-from-bosaso-to-addis-ababa",
    "summary": "The International Organization for Migration repatriated 56 Ethiopian migrants, including 10 unaccompanied children, from Bosaso to Ethiopia in a coordinated operation with Somali authorities, highlighting the ongoing humanitarian challenges along the migration route.",
    "content": "The International Organization for Migration (IOM) repatriated 56 Ethiopian migrants from the port city of Bosaso in Somalia’s semi-autonomous Puntland region on Wednesday, flying them back to Addis Ababa. The group included 10 unaccompanied children, underscoring the vulnerability of those attempting the perilous journey across the Gulf of Aden to reach Gulf states in search of economic opportunities.\n\nThis operation was conducted in collaboration with Somali authorities, who facilitated the transfer of migrants from detention centers to the Bosaso airport. Many of the returnees had been intercepted by Somali security forces while trying to board smugglers’ boats bound for Yemen, a common transit point for migrants aiming to reach Saudi Arabia and other Gulf countries.\n\nThe repatriation highlights the cyclical nature of migration from the Horn of Africa, where thousands of young people risk death from drowning, dehydration, and abuse by human traffickers. The IOM regularly assists voluntary returns for migrants who are stranded or choose to go home, emphasizing that this program aims to provide a safer alternative to irregular migration.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, this event serves as a reminder of the persistent instability and limited economic prospects in the region, which drive neighbors like Ethiopians to transit through Somalia. Many Somali families also have relatives who have undertaken similar journeys, and the news underscores the importance of supporting sustainable development and legal migration pathways.\n\nSomalia remains a source, transit, and destination country for mixed migration flows, with the IOM estimating that hundreds of thousands of migrants pass through the country annually en route to the Arabian Peninsula. The welfare of vulnerable groups, especially children traveling alone, continues to be a pressing humanitarian concern requiring coordinated regional responses.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Dalsan here: https://radiodalsan.com/2026/07/22/iom-flies-56-migrants-back-to-ethiopia/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=iom-flies-56-migrants-back-to-ethiopia",
